Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Task for you", "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.813645200238077*^9, 
  3.8136452051529303`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"62248969-557b-40b7-bab3-\
78db2ed0a906"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Task 1.",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " Above, we have used the function ",
 StyleBox["Classify", "CodeText"],
 " to implement the KNN algorithm. However, the KNN is simple enough as for \
you to try and implement it from scratch. In Mathematica, this mostly reduces \
to list manipulation. You may find the function ",
 StyleBox["DistanceMatrix", "CodeText"],
 " useful for this task."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8136452146056495`*^9, 3.8136452813428516`*^9}, {
  3.81364540193039*^9, 
  3.8136455152307734`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"25f0fdc0-7fa2-46d8-bb93-\
97cfb581b324"]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["Choosing K - What is the most appropriate value of \
K?", "Subsubsection"]], "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.813595816590769*^9},ExpressionUUID->"1dd03269-d7b0-4e8d-a556-\
d9e906ad2320"],

Cell["\<\
In order to test what is the best value of k, let us assume that we have a \
test dataset consisting of 100 points in each of the classes used to train \
the classifier.\
\>", "Text",
